ce:section.ce:para:
Density functional theory (DFT) calculations are the most effective method to investigate the electronic structure of TOC and its complex with DA. The optical properties of the chemosensor were performed using B3LYP functional under the 6-31G* basis set. The polarizable continuous model (PCM) was used to calculate the solvent phase [50]. According to Koopmans theorem, the electron affinity (A) and ionisation energy (I) were calculated using EHOMO and ELUMO values as A = -ELUMO and I = - EHOMO. The highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) and lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) energies of TOC and TOC + DA are presented in Table S2. The frontier orbital was utilised to determine the molecule's stability and reactivity, which are defined by several metrics such as chemical potential (µ), energy gap (ΔE), softness (S), and chemical hardness (η). For example, a molecule with a lower energy gap has low excitation energy, low chemical hardness, and high stability. Calculated values of these parameters are displayed in Table 2
                        . The energy gap between the LUMO (- 1.920) and HOMO (- 6.133) of the TOC was found to be 4.213 eV, while upon complexation of TOC with DA the energy gap between the LUMO (-1.806) and HOMO (-4.812) decreases to 3.006 eV (Fig. 9
                        ). This reduction in the band gap of TOC-DA is strongly endorsed by the prominent bathochromic shift noticed in the UV–vis absorption spectra upon addition of DA to the TOC. Therefore, these findings supported the experimental results and depicted the excellent stability of the TOC sensor complex.
